One, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight, nine, ten.
This is Thursday morning, October of the 30th, and I have the pleasure and honor of chatting with John Sharp, whom I remember as a fine, fine student leader here.
to introduce yourself to anyone who may listen or read this material in the future.
Describe your family background.
Where'd you grow up?
Where'd you go to high school?
What did parents do?
Introduce yourself to them.
I grew up in Placido, Texas, population somewhat under 200, maybe somewhat under 100.
It's a little town in Victoria County, just south of Victoria.
There were two towns south of Victoria, one Bloomington.
And that's where all the people lived that didn't want anybody to know they drank whiskey.
And Placido is where everybody lived that had the whiskey stores.
And so the stores stayed open until quite late at night to allow the folks in Bloomington to come over without being seen.
My father worked 38 years as a gauger in the oil field for Magnolia and then later Mobile Oil in the oil fields around Vanderbilt.
My mother was a teacher for nearly 30 years, fifth grade teacher in Bloomington Elementary in Placido.
elementary school.
My mother went to the University of Texas.
My father didn't go to college.
He was wounded in World War II in the island of Leyte in the Philippines and was in the battles of New Guinea.
And my brother also didn't go to college.
My sister graduated from the University of Texas and I'm the first of my family to go anywhere other than the University of Texas, including all cousins and everybody else.
They all went to the University of Texas.
I was in high school.
Manuela Gutierrez one day just nominated me for class president and nobody else was.
And so I became it and I guess got used to it.
And so in high school I was student body president in several things.
And which high school?
Bloomington High School, which is at the time, it would be 2A now, but my graduating class, 52 kids.

When I was 11 years old, I will never forget it, my mother was very, very insistent that at a very young age we decide what we're going to be and bye George, all these kids are going to go to college.
And I remember I had a lot of animals and including tons of pigeons.
I raised homing pigeons when I was just a little kid.
One of them got run over on the side of the road and broke his wing.
And I took a Popsicle stick and stuck it together
And it must not have been broken very badly, because about eight weeks later, the pigeon was flying again.
And I can remember it as if it was yesterday, because it is the reason I went to A&M.
The pigeon was flying.
My mother, on her daily insistence, I was watching the pigeon fly.
The pigeon's name was Pidge.
I thought that was an amazing deal.
She did, too.
And she said, you know, you ought to be a veterinarian.
And I said, OK, Mom.
suits me fine.
I was 11 years old.
I'll just be a veterinarian.
Where do I go to school to be a veterinarian?
She said, you have to go to a place called Texas A&M University, which I've never heard of or been to.
And I said, great.
Now that that's settled, I can get on with fourth grade or whatever I was in at the time.
And she started telling everybody, oh, John's going to go to A&M.
He's going to be an Aggie.
And for Christmas, I started getting these Aggie sweatshirts and
Aggie paraphernalia.
By the time I was in high school, that was a very foregone conclusion.
And that's where I was going.
Still had never seen the place.
My teacher my senior year was Mabel White, whose son later was a congressman.
His name was Joe White from that area.
W-Y-A-T-T. W-Y-A-T-T. And he was a state representative that I eventually replaced.
And my mother taught him, and his mother taught me.
And she was the outstanding teacher of the year in Texas when I was in high school.
And she came to me one day and she said, you don't want to be a veterinarian.
And I said, you're right, Ms. White.
I can't stand the sight of blood.
I can't believe I'm going to go somewhere and be a veterinarian.
She said, you should be in government.
She gave me this little test.
And she probably made it up.
But anyway, the test said that.
And about that time, I came to A&M.
I went to the vet school with my father, my very first trip.
And first meal was at the Whataburger over here on Highway 6.
Went to see the veterinarian.
He said, why do you want to be a veterinarian?
And I said, well, I guess because they make a lot of money.
And he said, you don't want to be a veterinarian because you're not going to make very much money as a veterinarian.
And I said, works for me.
I'm out of here.
It was literally like that.
I said, Mrs. Wyatt was right.
And so I became a liberal arts major.
And then Gary Halter.
was my advisor, who remains a good friend, and he talked me into majoring in political science later on.
The Corps, I didn't know anything about the Corps.

I mean, I knew nothing about anything, but on that trip, I noticed I saw a whole bunch of uniforms, and there was a bunch of signs of people running for office, and I was kind of interested in all that kind of stuff.
And on the way back, we picked up a hitchhiker who was in uniform and had a little Aggie maroon and white bag.
And we get him in the car, me and a guy named Mike Olson, who came here one year and then didn't make it and went to some other school, I think ANI or someplace after his grade.
And I asked that guy, I said, what is this core thing?
And he said, you are just going to love it.
So it is just great.
I said, you know, my mother was in a fraternity, a sorority, and all my uncles and all, they thought that was a lot of fun.
I said, this is ten times better than fraternity.
If you want to be anything at A&M, you've got to be in the Corps.
And I said, well, you just talked me into it.
And I was literally filling out the little form, and I just checked Corps.
And so that's how I wound up at A&M.
I wish I could say, yeah, I was, you know, huge family background, and boy, they are all, you know, ten generations of Aggies, but it wasn't true.
It was a pigeon.
Alright, so you enrolled in the fall of 1968.
Describe that coming up here.
Who brought you?
What stuff did you bring with you?
You're not going to believe this story.
This story probably shouldn't be in the archives, but you're looking at the only kid that brought a fishing pole to fish camp.
That's marvelous.
I knew so little about it.
I showed up at the YMCA.
This guy in the car said we should go to fish camp because you're going to learn an awful lot there.
I met at the YMCA.
My dad
gave me a hug, dropped me off at the YMCA, and left.
And there was this crowd of people.
I'm going, what in the world is this?
I must have looked real lost.
And a guy named Chris Shaw, who you might have known.
He and Capron were good friends.
He was pretty active in student government and SCONA and some of that stuff.
He was one of Wayne Stark's boys, you know.
And he came over and he said, you look kind of lost.
Where are you from?
I told him, Placido.
He said, I'm from Garwood.
And we became instant friends.
He was the first guy that I met.
And so we went to fish camp.
Turns out when we get to fish camp, the family that owns the land there was, I forget their name.
I think their name was Giles.
Anyway, she was my teacher.
She was my English teacher in high school.
It turns out that she was walking around there.
I said, what are you doing here?
Now, fish camp was held up near Palestine.
Palestine.
And so anyway, we went through fish camp and then
Best thing I ever did.
I mean, I would recommend it highly to every kid that can because it gave me a sense of what everything was about and, you know, kind of put it all in perspective.
When you came to stay, what other stuff did you bring in addition to the fishing pole?
Oh, I brought the stuff.
I brought the stuff that they told me, you know, they, you know, foot locker full of, you know, all the stuff.
So that was pretty easy.
It was everything.
I do remember, though, dragging that footlocker down the hall and I was still a high school Harry, you know, hadn't been taken to the level that you're supposed to be as a fish, you know.
And I remember dragging it down the hall and this guy said, he kept hollering, Fish Jones, Fish Jones.
And I knew he wasn't talking to me and my name's not Jones.
And then eventually I figured out he was talking to me, but that was the wrong name.
So I turned around and said something like, hey, Frank, how you been?
He said,
blankety-blank, my name's not Frank, and so my name's not Jones either.
And he turned out to be the first sergeant of the outfit, so we got off to a real good start.
Did, as your parents left, did they give you any advice?
Well, my mother didn't come up.
She said her goodbyes at home.
No, my dad's real quiet.
He just, you know, he drove me up there, left me off at the YMCA building.
That may have been, except when he was dating my mother, the only time he was on a college campus.
I mean, he had never, except for that first trip in the spring, you know, when we came up and learned about
the corps and everything.
That was only his second trip and he dropped me off at the YMCA and wanted to get the heck out of the traffic and get back to Placido, Texas.
Alright, how did you get from the YMCA to whatever outfit?
Well, we went to fish camp from there and then when we got back from Palestine they had assigned us all outfits and we were all in
Do you have any idea how you came to be assigned to the outfit you were in?
Any reason for it?
Yeah, because I had put down veterinary medicine and everybody in the outfit, in the spring I put down veterinary medicine and everybody in the outfit was agriculture.
Everybody was agriculture except me.
And by that time I'd already changed to liberal arts so I was in an outfit with ag-eco majors and agronomy majors and all those guys were from ranching families
from the country as I was, but I was the only fish that was something other than an agriculture major.
And what outfit was it?
Squadron 6.
Did it have a nickname?
Savage 6.
Savage 6.
Flying Tigers.
Flying Tigers.
I bought the last six t-shirts.
They abolished it several years ago, I think, because of grades.
The day before they abolished it, I came down and bought the last six t-shirts Lupo had.
I still have them for
What was it like in the first few weeks to be a fish?
Oh, horrible.
Describe.
I thought I'd landed on another planet.
I just said, who are these people?
Oh, it was just, you know, it is one of those things I'm real glad I did.
Whether or not you would show me those circumstances again and I would go back and do that again, I hope I would have the courage to do it again.
But the physical part, I didn't mind.
It was the mental part.
stuff that was the toughest, you know, somebody screaming at you all the time.
As you look back though, this is the best thing that ever happened to me because the core really does have the system down.
You know, you heard a bunch of people say, oh, they did away with paddling or they did away with, you know, physical hazing or getting them up at 2 o'clock in the morning and running to the airport.
That didn't matter.
That isn't the stuff that trained you.

What trained you was you took all these high school heroes like me, most of which were something in high school or football stars or something like that, and took us down to a level that weighed down, just stripped us of all pretenses and pride and everything.
and then allowed us to work our way up as sophomores and juniors and seniors.
And it was, it's some of the best leadership, it's the best leadership formula I've seen.
And I think that's why so many people come out of their, not just excelling in the military, but excelling in business, you know,
Whatever they get in.
You had a fish-hole lady in a room.
Describe who that was and what your room was like.
What was in your freshman room?
Just four walls and a window and a little heater at the end.
I had several.
I had, my first roommate was a guy named Johnson.
but he was gone after the first semester.
His grades got real bad and he was gone.
And then my next roommate was a guy, a good guy named Glenn Honaker.
Still Honaker.
H-O-N-A-K-E-R from Fort Stockton.
He's now in charge of
like the largest pecan orchard that exists on the planet.
I mean, it's just huge.
If you fly over to Fort Stockton, you'll see all this greenery on one side, and that's his pecan orchards, him and another guy.
And my last roommate was, before I went on core staff, my last roommate was Chris Roberts, who remains one of my very best friends, as does Glen.
And he's head of the Federal Land Bank near Lubbock out there.
And Chris is from Tohoka, which means bad water.
He lives in level land right now.
And we were roommates until my senior year.
My senior year, I was elected student body president and chosen to be on as programs officer for core staff.
And my roommate there was Ray Kopecky, who was the inspector general, little fireball from Pasadena.
that everyone in the Corps loved to hate because he was Inspector General and would show up at your doorstep at 6 o'clock in the morning.
During that first fall, were you a victim of what today would be defined as hazing, and if so, describe some of it.
Yeah, I thought hazing was getting up at 6 in the morning with a whistle blowing in your ear.
Yeah, I mean, we had
We had, it was all pretty good natured.
I mean, we, I learned how to do a couple hundred pushups pretty quick that I never thought I could do.
And so we had to do that stuff.

And yeah, if we messed up bad enough, we'd go, we'd all have to go out on the hall and, or in the steam showers or something and, you know, grab butterflies, which was not the best thing for your knees, I guess.
And, and.
Any paddles used?
Only.
Only at the end of the year when everybody knew this was a rite of passage from being a fish to something else.
That's the only time when everybody kind of agreed to it.
We were a pretty cautious outfit.
One of the reasons for that is the first week we were here we had an Air Force qualifying test.
It wasn't hazing.
We had to run a mile

for Air Force ROTC, and in that mile, I was running along with a guy from Hondo, one of the best guys in the world, named Tom Stein, and I looked at him as we were going to the finish line, and he was turning blue, and I looked at him and I said, Tom, are you okay?
And he got to the finish line and died.
It was the first death that year on campus, and he died right next to me and our first sergeant, Bill Hall, was the first one there and tried to give him artificial
you know, respiration and it just didn't work.
And he, so he died with all of us looking at that.

And aside from the loss of Tom, it was the first silver taps that year, aside from the loss of him, it was, you know, everybody was in the back of their mind was saying, well, what if they had just had us out, you know, running because somebody did something.
And that I think weighed pretty heavily on those upperclassmen's mind that whole year.
And so we didn't, we didn't, uh,
There wasn't anything out of the ordinary, I mean, I don't think.
Let's go to the child hall now as a freshman.
Describe the routine there.
The routine there, that's my worst place.
I absolutely hated the place.
And that is one of the primary reasons that I became involved in student government.
Because after about two or three weeks of that, I looked up the rules and said, okay,
how do you get out of this?
I mean I got tired of eating under the table and being screamed at while I was eating.
My food just didn't digest very well while I was being screamed at.

And so I would find the Apollo Club that met breakfast on Monday and I would find which club met on Tuesday and which club met in the evening and by the time that first semester was over with I was racking up lots of points for the outfit in terms of the numbers of clubs that I
I joined.
The chow hall was just absolutely nerve-racking for me.
I never ever got used to it.
And I would always find someplace to eat.
There was a 7-Eleven or something over here and I'd go over there and get a piece of bologna and cheese and eat that and go to my meeting.
And I lost 27 pounds my freshman year, my first semester.
I'm not a big fan of Duncan Dining Hall.
Did you and your buddies ever attempt any pranks that freshman year in the child hall?
No, not in there.
We kept ours at other places.
What about some of that good bull?
Well, we had one of the guys in my outfit that lived across the hall from me.
We used to always say we were roommates, but we never were roommates.
It was Rick Perry.
We were in the same outfit.
And one of the things that happened that I'm sure we'll all deny is we had this one particular upperclassman that was a real jerk.
And everybody knew he was a jerk.
And we knew if we did something to him, nobody would get too mad.
And so Rick found some M80s somewhere.
Some what?
M80s, big firecrackers, just a little short of dynamite, I guess.
And we discovered that if you go up to the second floor above the bathrooms, that they were all linked together.
All four floors of the bathrooms were linked together.
And if you dropped that lit, it would stay lit, and flushed it, that it would explode somewhere around the next one.
And so my job on that particular Saturday morning

was to because we knew he came in and read the paper on usually stall number two and I sat there and waited for him to come in he came in he sat down and I simply held two fingers out for Mr. Perry who was above us and I heard the flush above and I just kind of sat there and watched and it literally vaulted him off the camo
Thank God the door was open because the door flew open and he was laying there with his underwear around his ankles on his all fours with the newspaper broken around his neck.
And I was just sitting there, oh my God, we killed this poor bastard.
I mean, we killed this guy.
And I just left.
I mean, I went up there and I just went to my room and cowered in the corner.
And Rick comes in and said, how'd it work?
I said, man, you just wouldn't believe it.
But it was a serious impact.
I mean, that water in a little inch and a half pipe all coming out that one commode was awesome.
It was one of the more awesome displays of nature.
So he really wasn't hurt?
Well, he wasn't hurt, no.
But he never, ever, ever figured out.
But he never changed.
He always was like that.
And so Christmas time, Christmas time we did get some chickens.
And after he left, we had been in there doing push-ups, and we took the door hinges out, and we put pencils in there so that you could just kick it in and break it, and he never noticed it.
So he left for Christmas.
We stayed an extra few hours.
And when he did, we put four or five chickens in his room with enough food to last a month and plenty of water and stuff like that.
And you can imagine what his room looked like when he got back.
It was not very pretty.
Where did you all get the chickens?
Somewhere over in...
In Poulter Science?
No, we actually went and got them from some farmer around here, I think toward Milliken, somewhere like that.
You mean y'all bought them?
Oh yeah, we paid good money for those chickens, a buck or two apiece.
An honest cash transaction.
Oh yeah, we didn't steal the chicken.
That's good.
What was special about, as you look back, what was special about those chickens?
though you were praising the Corps, what did those first two or three years do to you and your personality that were important?
Well, I think what the Corps does is it teaches you, it operates on the theory of in order to be a leader, you've got to know what it feels like to be led.
And I think that's what
I think that right there is what makes it special.
All the other stuff is kind of side benefits.
You get to make long lasting friends that are going to be your friends forever and ever.
And the closeness and the camaraderie in the spirit.
I think the Corps has a special role.
If you had asked me back then, if you had told me in 1972
on the day that I graduated in May that, you know, this school is going to be 50,000 kids and 2,000 or less are going to be in the core.
You think they'll still stand up for football games?
You think they'll still do all, have midnight yell practice?
I said, in no way in the world that would exist.
And the fact that that is just as strong or stronger than it ever has been before, I think is a testament to the kind of kids that come here, but I think it also is a testament to the core

maybe kind of keeps the fire stoked and and stuff and as part of it uh academics uh you you know you gradually you gradually shifted or or you shifted from veterinary medicine well i never never never never signed up for veterinary medicine so that you shifted over the summer you registered the first semester liberal arts as liberal arts
And do you remember some courses that first fall?
Courses and or instructors or advisors?
My favorite political science professor was Gary Halter.
I thought he was really good.
I liked his courses a lot.
I didn't get into his until I was into my sophomore year and stuff like that.
But my best course, funny you should ask this, that I did the worst in was American history.
And we had this professor that had this unbelievable photographic memory of the Civil War.
And it was so fascinating.
And I'm not saying this because this professor is in the room.
But it was so fascinating that I never took a note.
I sat in the back of the class.
I remember that class specifically.
I sat in the back of that class.
just mesmerized at how in the hell does this guy remember the dates and stuff of all this stuff.
And we would look at each other and we refought the Civil War right there in that.
And I never had any of that in high school, you know.
And that was the best course I took at A&M.
It really was high school.
And there's lots of kids that will say the same thing.
Best course I took.
But I think I got a D in it.
I never took a note and I could not remember those damn dates that you were always asking for on the test.
And trivia, was Rick in that same section?
I don't know.
I don't know if he was or not.
Probably, I don't know.
It was a required course, wasn't it?
Everybody had to take History 1, but there were many sections.
I don't know.
This is a big, big...
There must have been 300 kids in this thing.
I think I had both of y'all in class.
I'm not sure, but I think I did.
Probably so.
That would have been our freshman, sophomore year freshman, maybe?
Probably freshman.
Freshman, yeah.
Because that was normal for a liberal arts, you know, kind of the general.
Do you remember?
It was American history, right?
Yeah, yeah.
Do you remember how many hours you normally took per semester?
A heck of a lot more than my kids taking now.
I mean, I took 18 and it wasn't any big deal.
I graduated on time, but the only way I graduated on time was I went to a couple of summer schools.

And now my son, who is going to the wrong school, UT, TU, you know those kids take 12 hours and 14 hours and if they get past 15 they go, oh my God, we're going to stress these kids out and they can't make it anymore.
But I, you know, I'm wondering if one semester I didn't take 21, but I knew I took 18 many different times.
Describe
Particularly your freshman year if you can.
But what was the typical routine for you on a class day?
What time did you get up?
What did you do?
When?
I guess the whistle started blowing at, I don't know, I guess it was damned early.
It seemed like to me six, I'm guessing.
would put on a uniform, double-check each other, make sure there weren't any smudges.
Did you have any upperclassmen's room you had to care for that fish year?
No.
And then I went out on the hall to be in the squad that you were in, and then some, you know, sophomore comes by.
We use nice terms for the archives.
Some sophomore would come by, check us all, scream as all of us.
We were fortunate in my squad that we had this one kid named Merritt,
I don't think he was there after the first semester.
But he just delighted in wearing white socks with his uniform.
And they screamed at him all the time.
And he just loved it.
I was not one that was big on loving that.
But they screamed at him most times.
So anyway, we'd go out there.

They'd inspect us, ask us a lot of questions, ask us what was on the inscription on Guyon Hall, the inscription on Lawrence Sullivan Ross, all this kind of stuff, the definition of a freshman, all this kind of stuff, all of which I still remember.
and then went out into formation in the quad.
Corps staff walked by.
We marched to Mourning Child, did that bit, came back, cleaned up your room, got it ready for inspection in case somebody was going to come by.
And then went to class.
And for the first semester of our fish year, we were required to come back for noon.
They did away with that because classes just didn't start matching after the first semester, which I thought was great.
One more time, I didn't have to go in that place.
And usually we'd go to class until then, and then I would always have some meat that night.
At the end of my freshman year, a bunch of guys in the outfit, there was a guy named Kirby Brown, who is now the Director of Public Relations for Parks and Wildlife, was a fish class president then.
Some guys in my outfit came to me and some upperclassmen said, hey, you ought to run for sophomore class president.
I said, what makes you think I'm uniquely qualified to do that?
And he said, well, your name, Sharp, you can do so much with it.
And I said, yeah, you know, I bet that's right.
You know, everybody's always asking me, are you Sharp, Chris Sharp, and all this kind of stuff?
He said, yeah, you've got a great name.
And so there were four or five people running.
So I put my name in, and we printed up a bunch of signs that said, look Sharp, think Sharp, vote Sharp.
And we plastered them all over the corps.
Didn't put them anywhere else.
You know, I don't know if anybody else voted for me on the civilian side.
But then won.
And then in that, then got to know Caperton and Lane Cruz and all of those folks.
That was kind of a whole new world because I was also in the student senate at the time.
And then at the end of my sophomore year, ran for student life chairman, which I guess, I don't know if they still have that or not.
It's kind of a cabinet deal.
And then, and Roger Miller was student body vice president, who was real close to Kent.
And Roger and I met once a week and told each other we wouldn't run against each other.
Both of us knew the line.
And then when the time came, sure enough, Roger and I ran against each other for student body president.
And Roger made one very terrible mistake, and that is the week before the election, we were both being interviewed by the battalion.
And they asked Roger, I said, Roger, would you be willing to consider any alternatives to the bonfire?
And Roger, being the open-minded kind of guy that he is, said, well, yeah, I'd consider some alternatives.
And they asked me, and I said, well, of course not.
That's heresy.
Wouldn't do it and all this kind of stuff.
And that was it.
I mean, I could have gone fishing that last week because it was over with then.
Do you remember what the margin was in the election?
It was pretty serious.
I mean, the Corps was really being sensed.
The Corps and Walton Hall and Hart Hall and all those people.
